She quickly rose from first violin to conductor as the small group became a chamber orchestra, assuming leadership in 1890.
The group played and toured until 1920 and played more than 6000 concerts.
Caroline B. Nichols (1864-1939) was an American violinist, conductor and founder of the Fadette Ladies Orchestra (known as the Fadettes of Boston).
Nichols was a founding member of Marion Osgood's Ladies Orchestra, however about four years later she was a founding member of the Fadettes of Boston in 1888, a sextet, including Ethel Atwood.
She led the Fadettes for more than thirty years.
